---
import BaseLayout from '@layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "Article",
  "headline": "3-6 Month Milestones: Development Checklist",
  "description": "Complete developmental milestones checklist for 3-6 month olds. Physical, cognitive, language, and social-emotional milestones from CDC guidelines.",
  "author": {
    "@type": "Organization",
    "name": "AgeExpectations"
  }
};

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What milestones should a 4-month-old achieve?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "At 4 months, most babies roll tummy to back, push up on arms during tummy time, coo and babble, smile socially, and track moving objects with their eyes."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "When do babies start sitting up?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Most babies sit with support around 4-6 months and sit independently around 6-8 months. Some sit earlier or later — both can be normal."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How do I know if my baby has good head control?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Good head control means your baby can hold their head steady when upright, keep their head up during tummy time, and turn their head to follow sounds or objects."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---

<BaseLayout title="3-6 Month Milestones: Development Checklist" description="Complete developmental milestones checklist for 3-6 month olds. Physical, cognitive, language, and social milestones from CDC guidelines." schema={schema} pageType="Article">
  <article class="article">
    <header class="article-header">
      <h1>3-6 Month Milestones: Development Checklist</h1>
      <p class="article-meta">Ages 3-6 months · Updated March 2026</p>
    </header>

    <div class="topic-nav">
      <a href="/ages/3-6-months/">Overview</a>
      <a href="/ages/3-6-months/milestones/">Milestones</a>
      <a href="/ages/3-6-months/sleep/">Sleep</a>
      <a href="/ages/3-6-months/feeding/">Feeding</a>
      <a href="/ages/3-6-months/health/">Health</a>
    </div>

    <div class="article-content">
      <p>Between 3 and 6 months, your baby transforms from a newborn into an interactive, curious little person. This guide covers the major developmental milestones to expect, based on CDC and AAP guidelines.</p>

      <h2>4 Month Milestones</h2>
      
      <h3>Physical/Motor</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Holds head steady when upright</li>
        <li>Pushes up on arms during tummy time</li>
        <li>May roll from tummy to back</li>
        <li>Brings hands to mouth</li>
        <li>Reaches for and grasps toys</li>
        <li>Bears weight on legs when feet are on a hard surface</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Language/Communication</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Cooing and making vowel sounds ("oooo," "aaaa")</li>
        <li>Turns head toward sounds</li>
        <li>Makes sounds when looking at toys or people</li>
        <li>Begins to babble with consonant sounds</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Cognitive</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Tracks moving objects with eyes</li>
        <li>Looks around with curiosity</li>
        <li>Watches faces closely</li>
        <li>Recognizes familiar people and objects from a distance</li>
        <li>Beginning to understand object permanence</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Social/Emotional</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Smiles spontaneously (social smiles)</li>
        <li>Likes to play with people</li>
        <li>May cry when play stops</li>
        <li>Copies some movements and facial expressions</li>
        <li>Recognizes and prefers familiar people</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>6 Month Milestones</h2>
      
      <h3>Physical/Motor</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Rolls over in both directions (front to back, back to front)</li>
        <li>Begins to sit without support</li>
        <li>Supports weight on legs and might bounce when standing</li>
        <li>Rocks back and forth, sometimes crawling backward before forward</li>
        <li>Transfers objects from one hand to another</li>
        <li>Reaches for and grasps objects with entire hand</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Language/Communication</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Responds to sounds by making sounds</li>
        <li>Strings vowels together when babbling ("ah," "eh," "oh")</li>
        <li>Likes taking turns with parent while making sounds</li>
        <li>Responds to own name</li>
        <li>Makes squealing noises</li>
        <li>Begins to say consonant sounds (jabbering with "m," "b")</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Cognitive</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Looks around at things nearby</li>
        <li>Shows curiosity about things and tries to get things that are out of reach</li>
        <li>Begins to pass things from one hand to the other</li>
        <li>Explores objects by putting them in mouth</li>
        <li>Recognizes familiar faces from across the room</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Social/Emotional</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Knows familiar faces and begins to know if someone is a stranger</li>
        <li>Likes to look at self in mirror</li>
        <li>Laughs and makes happy sounds</li>
        <li>Responds to other people's emotions and often seems happy</li>
        <li>Likes to look at self in a mirror</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Tummy Time Progression</h2>
      <p>Tummy time is crucial for development:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>3 months:</strong> Lifts head and chest, supports on forearms</li>
        <li><strong>4 months:</strong> Pushes up on extended arms, may roll</li>
        <li><strong>5 months:</strong> Reaches for toys while on tummy</li>
        <li><strong>6 months:</strong> May pivot in circles, prepares for crawling</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Vision Development</h2>
      <p>Your baby's vision is rapidly improving:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>3 months:</strong> Follows moving objects, recognizes faces</li>
        <li><strong>4 months:</strong> Depth perception developing, sees across room</li>
        <li><strong>5 months:</strong> Color vision nearly adult-like</li>
        <li><strong>6 months:</strong> Good color vision, tracks moving objects smoothly</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Hearing and Sound</h2>
      <p>Your baby is learning about sound:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Turns toward sounds and voices</li>
        <li>Responds to own name by 6 months</li>
        <li>Enjoys music and rhythmic sounds</li>
        <li>Startles to loud noises</li>
        <li>Begins to understand tone of voice</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Red Flags: When to Be Concerned</h2>
      <p>Talk to your pediatrician if your baby:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Doesn't watch faces or track moving objects by 3 months</li>
        <li>Doesn't smile by 3 months</li>
        <li>Doesn't make sounds or coo by 4 months</li>
        <li>Doesn't bring hands to mouth by 4 months</li>
        <li>Has trouble moving one or both eyes</li>
        <li>Doesn't respond to loud sounds</li>
        <li>Seems very stiff or very floppy</li>
        <li>Doesn't push down with legs when feet are on a hard surface</li>
        <li>Has difficulty getting things to mouth</li>
        <li>Doesn't make vowel sounds ("ah," "eh," "oh") by 6 months</li>
        <li>Doesn't laugh or make squealing sounds by 6 months</li>
        <li>Seems very irritable or difficult to soothe</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Supporting Development</h2>
      <p>Simple activities help your baby thrive:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Tummy time:</strong> Several short sessions daily</li>
        <li><strong>Talking:</strong> Narrate your day, respond to their sounds</li>
        <li><strong>Reading:</strong> Board books with bright pictures</li>
        <li><strong>Playing:</strong> Peek-a-boo, patty-cake, singing</li>
        <li><strong>Exploration:</strong> Safe objects with different textures</li>
        <li><strong>Mirror play:</strong> Babies love looking at themselves</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="faq-section">
        <h2>Is This Normal? — Common Questions</h2>
        
        <div class="faq-item">
          <p class="faq-question">My baby isn't rolling at 5 months. Should I worry?</p>
          <p class="faq-answer">Rolling timelines vary. Some babies roll at 3 months, others not until 6-7 months. If your baby is progressing in other areas (head control, reaching) and your pediatrician isn't concerned, it's likely fine. Keep doing tummy time.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <p class="faq-question">When should my baby start crawling?</p>
          <p class="faq-answer">Most babies crawl between 7-10 months, but some skip crawling entirely and go straight to walking. There's a wide range of normal. Focus on tummy time and floor play.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <p class="faq-question">My baby doesn't respond to their name at 6 months. Is this okay?</p>
          <p class="faq-answer">Responding to name typically develops between 6-9 months. Some babies take longer. If your baby makes eye contact, smiles, and responds to other sounds, mention it at your next checkup but don't panic.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <p class="faq-question">Is it normal for my baby to be fussy during tummy time?</p>
          <p class="faq-answer">Yes, many babies resist tummy time initially. Start with very short sessions (1-2 minutes), use toys for distraction, and do it when baby is well-rested. It gets easier with practice.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
